In the first week, our Scrum team of five people started working on the CampusCare project with TRELLO being our planning and task management tool. Our choice of SDG 3: Good Health and Well-Being is explained by problematic access to healthcare among students within campus. We have created a Product Vision Document, have done the stakeholder analysis, and created 12 user stories which were added at once as cards to our Trello Product Backlog. The MoSCoW technique was applied to the prioritization of these stories with the help of color-coded Trello labels (red=Critical, yellow=High, green=Medium, blue=Low). A preliminary product backlog was developed with 18 items in the form of Trello cards, each item had a checklist, attachments, assignments, and due dates. Our Trello board was configured with six lists (Product Backlog, Sprint 1 Backlog, Sprint 2 Backlog, Doing, Review, Done) and filled all cards with all the necessary information. GitHub repository was also configured and adequately structured in terms of folders to store documentation. It was ended with a Sprint 1 Planning Meeting during which we transferred some of the cards in Product Backlog to Sprint 1 Backlog and divided them into tasks to be done, assigning them to teams. All the tasks that had to be performed throughout the week were scheduled and managed with the help of Trello only where real-time updates, comments and files attachments were implemented. The Trello snapshots of our board of populated backlog, priority tags, and sprint planning of week 1 are also testimonies to our thorough planning.
